gomodel:SYNGO_1253  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 2: \"ADAM10 localization and activity influence spine morphology\"\nFigure 3: \"Timing of ADAM10-dependent effect on spine morphology\"\n\n8/11/2017 Pim\n- Recap: ADAM10 cleaves N-cadherin (a homophilic interactin pre and postsynaptic adhesion molecule). Mislocalization of ADAM10 with a TAT-fused competing peptide or inhibition of ADAM10 activity with TIMP-1 results in spine morphology changes and different synaptic transmission (AMPAR composition, AMPA activity) in vitro and in vivo. I think that the role of N-cadherin in this story is illustrated in a correlational rather than a experimental fashion. No effect on cell adhesion is shown.. Experimental description: Rat hippocampal cultures were used for the in vitro experiments.\nLiteral:\nHippocampal neuronal primary cultures were prepared from embryonic day 18-19 rat hippocampi as described previously (Piccoli et al., 2007).\nLiteral:\nAnimal treatment. Two-week-old mice (Charles River) received a single intraperitoneal injection of either TAT-Pro (3 nmol/g) or TAT-Ala peptide (3 nmol/g) diluted in sterile saline solution (Marcello et al., 2007)." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2949-9725" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0662-9523" ;
        dc:date           "2018-01-26" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_1253" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

